A TCP flag is a control bit in the TCP header used to manage and control TCP connections (establish, transfer data, and terminate connections).

                                                                                                                                                                    
ðŸ”¸ URG (Urgent)

Indicates urgent data is present
Urgent Pointer field is valid
Data should be processed immediately

ðŸ”¸ PSH (Push)

Tells receiver to process data immediately
Do not wait for buffer to fill
Common in interactive applications

ðŸ”¸ FIN (Finish)

Gracefully closes the connection
Sender has no more data to send
Used in normal TCP termination

ðŸ”¸ RST (Reset)

Immediately terminates the connection
Sent when connection is invalid or refused
Seen during port scanning or crashes
